segments.text: and we were talking about how you advance in the service, and we were talking about the values, and you mentioned some of the values.
And we said basically that you didn't think there was a difference between the business or professional world and how you get ahead in the military.
You felt it's the same type of leadership.
I wanted to ask you, did you consider yourself ambitious?
Few people make it to generals.
I never felt like I was ambitious.
I never felt along the line that I was shooting to be a general.
I never felt that way.
Just deep down, you know, I might look like I was to others that I was, you know, bucking for a generalship, but I never felt that my goal was to be a general.
Just never disgusted with anything.
I never talked to Catherine about it.
Or my brothers, as close as we are.
I never said, hell, I'm going to be a general.
Just never did.
I just felt that I enjoyed doing what I was doing and trying to do the best job I can.
And it just happened.
Were you really surprised then when you did get that telephone call?
I really did.
I wasn't surprised.
Let me say this, I've met some brigadier generals and even major generals as a colonel that I often wonder, how in the hell did they become generals?
And here I am a colonel.
You know, but uh... You just didn't think they had the quality to be general officers?
No, I just didn't think they had the quality and didn't know how they did it and then found out later it was political and I said, well,
Here I am, a full colonel, and these guys are Brigadier General.
I'll give you an example.
When I had a direct support group as a colonel, my commander was the second one that took over.
You want me to mention names?
Only if you want to.
Well, let me just say he was a commander.
He was a Brigadier General commanding the Direct Support Brigade.
377 Brigade is what Support Brigade is what they called it.
And after I was around him, I said to myself, you know, I said, God, dang, how did this guy get to be a general?
Hell, he don't know how to command.
He don't know how to lead.
He don't know how to organize his staff.
He let people, you know, well, his people, his own staff was just
doing things to me down here in a group that I was trying to ruin me.
I said, I'm not going to put up with that stuff.
And I'd go to him.
I'd complain to him.
He wouldn't do nothing about it.
Well, as it turned out, I made Brigadier.
He made Brigadier.
He was still a Brigadier.
Then he got relieved because of his uncouth attitude and uncouth
doings.
He went to Fort Hood one time and took his brigade headquarters, and he, the corps commander, three-star general, had a party, banquet.
And this brigadier general had a few drinks.
Next thing you know, he's putting his hand under the waitress's dress.
No kidding?
Yeah!
Right?
Right!
In fact, we had a party for him in Beaumont.
the red carpet in.
It was brand new carpet, red motel, brand new plush.
And we had a party for him and we had all our wives there and we had this dinner party and one of the officers come to me and says, Colonel Kokonos, what's the general over there?
So I looked around and sure enough he had his iron hand underneath the waitress's dress.
And then later on in the evening, the waitress came to me and complained to me about it.
I would think so.
Oh, sure.
She was furious.

Well, when I heard about his episode at Fort Hood, he was at the Corps Commander's banquet or dinner party, and the girl, the waitress that he put his hand under her skirt, was the warrant officer's wife who was on the Corps Commander's staff.
So much for him.
That was the end of him.
Fifth Army got rid of him quick.
Oh, yeah.
So in other words, you'd say that there are, in every organization, even in the elites of the military, you have undesirables that somehow get up there.
How do they get up there?
I don't know.
I don't know how they get up there.
They might have done well.
before they got there, but after they get there, they change.
Oh, I see.
They change.
I've seen it.
Probably true.
He changed, and this 90th Army Reserve Commander, he changed.
So, you have them.
In every organization.
In every organization.
Now, when you retired, do you remember what you thought on the day of your retirement?
Do you remember how you felt?
I felt kind of sad.
I didn't feel like that I was ready to retire.
Yeah.
And as it turned out, my records showed I had another year to go.
No kidding?
Really?
Really.
And somebody messed it up.
And you could have been, well, at least one of the three to go up for a promotion.
Yeah, I could have.
Oh, I read a document.
When RCPAC, the St. Louis Reserve Personnel Department, sent me my retirement papers,
Retirement date was 78 instead of 77.
I said, oh, what the hell.
It wouldn't do me any good to try to stir that up.
So I just said it was just the break of the game, I guess.
But I was satisfied, Terry.
I was satisfied to make Brigadier General.
Absolutely.
Oh, I was.
And it didn't disappoint me because I didn't get promoted further.

Would you say that making generalship was, whenever we take a look at a career, I always like to take a look at what we call successes and shortcomings, not necessarily failures, but would you put generalship, making the rank, as one of the successes, right?
Right.
And the command positions that you had and the schools that you had, what would you put as the shortcomings?
Was there anything that you felt that, gee, I really could have done better here, or I could have done something I didn't quite carry through here?
I can't recall any shortcomings because I think I'd have got promoted to general earlier if the 9th Division would have stayed intact.
See, I'd already made my mark on division artillery, and General Kidwell

who was my division bigoted general, Kickwell, who was my division commander, if he had been promoted to major general, I'd have been brought right along with him because I did a good job for him, a damn good job for him.
So as far as shortcomings, I was always fighting shortcomings by living in Beaumont because Beaumont did not have any reserves.
any high headquarter units here.
All we had was battalion or lieutenant colonel.
They had the school, but when I organized the 173rd Direct Support Group, that's the highest headquarters I've ever been in Beaumont.
That's certainly an accomplishment.
Well, I felt so, you know, that they asked me to take that over and bring it to Beaumont.
And Beaumont spread it high.
I got newspaper clippings about the new unit in Beaumont.
And Beaumont was proud.
And by the way, we received.
Well received.
When I got promoted to Brigadier General, the Chamber of Commerce threw a reception for me.
Really?
I was the first.
Oh, great.
What they did, the way they did it.
You were the first?
I was the first Beaumonter to be promoted to general rank.
Native Beaumont.
I was born and raised here.
Native Beaumont.
I was the first Beaumont to be promoted to general rank that I know of, that the chamber knows of.
I was the first reservist in Beaumont to be promoted to general rank.
And it wasn't easy.
It was hard because there were no units in this area.
You know, Houston had some general law, but dang, Houston was playing, you know, they got a lot of competition over there.
San Antone and Dallas and Fort Worth.
And when the Albuquerque deal came up, I was really surprised.
And certainly an accomplishment, though.
Well, the Chamber of Commerce was really great about it.
Newspapers and the radios and TV.
Were you interviewed on television or anything?
I was interviewed on television.
I told them practically what I'm telling you, that I'm proud that Beaumont has a general officer from this area.
And today, I'm called upon all the time to be at some ceremonies.
Really?
Yeah.
Even now that you're retired?
That I'm retired.
Do they want you to put your uniform on?
Want me to put my uniform on in 10 ceremonies?
The city of Beaumont, two years ago or a year ago,
Let me try to get my dates straight now.
A year ago, dedicated the Civic Center complex, the $34 million complex.
They asked me to be, they asked me as Brigadier General Mike P. Kokonos to be the master of ceremonies in uniform and to work the program up.
And I did.
I had flyovers.
Really?
Oh, yeah.
That's neat.
The minute the four...
planes from Ellington Field flew over, we sang the Star Spangled Banner.
People came to me afterwards and they had tears in their eyes.
They said, we couldn't help it, but the minute we sang the Star Spangled Banner and those planes came over, zooming like they did, it was emotional for them.
Just the other day, when Bob Crippen
You know the space shuttle?
The mayor of Beaumont called me in to sit in, to be with him on the committee.
He organized three weeks before Crippen came to help put on the celebration.
And he asked me to put on the parade for him.
Now I didn't, they cited, the publicity was General Coconose and General Coconose, but I didn't put on my uniform that day because I was putting the parade together.
So I didn't feel like I needed to do that.

I'm asked to, like Congressman Brooks, he came into town, they had appreciation dinner for him about a year or so, a year ago, and they asked me to lead the Pledge of Allegiance and asked me would I wear my uniform.
I said, sure.
I'm chairman of the Lamar University ROTC committee out there.
It's called the Military Advisory Committee of Lamar University.
I'm chairman of it.
And there's always functions in the ROTC.
So I always put on my uniform and go out there and present medals or make a speech.
Well, this is, I think, one of the aspects of becoming a general officer.
There's so much interaction once you become a general officer, so much more interaction with the community and with the military.
And do you think that that plays a role?
Do they pick general officers because they're good or strong personalities?
Do you think that plays a role?
I think that plays a role.
I think the rank plays a role.
People love general.
They love it.
When I tell them I'm a general, they take another look.
Really?
Oh, yeah.
So I think the rank.
But then the man comes into play.
If he can carry the rank well, he'll be asked to participate, and he'll be asked for services to help celebrate.
If he can?
If he can't, they won't.
And I know a couple of Brigadier Generals who moved into Beaumont working here for corporations, and they're not asked to do anything.
Maybe they don't want to be asked.
Maybe they're through.
For example, San Stephen's Episcopal Church asked me to come out on Flag Day and present them a flag that flew over the Capitol.
So I did.

I went out there, Catherine and I, and I wore my uniform, I wore my dress blues, and got up in front of the congregation and presented the flag and had it blessed, took communion with them, participated in the service with them, and they were just thrilled with that.
come up and they look at your ribbons and they look at, you know, they don't know what to do.
A lot of people really don't know too much about the Army.
And they look at your ribbons, you know, and they hesitate to ask you a question.
So I, you know, I kind of lead them a little bit too.
I says, you know what this is?
What is that?
Well, that's a purple heart.
Purple heart.
You know, they say purple heart.
So that's what the purple heart looks like.
I say, yeah, that's a purple heart.
So we started.
And they'd come up and see the boards, general boards.
So the community, I have to say I've been well received here.
That's great.
I go to the YMCA, and it's not Mike, it's the general.
Judge Fisher is the federal judge.
He and I are really real friends.
We're true friends.
And it's always general.
And I'll go to the Kiwanis Club, it's general, and I'll go to the church, it's general, and I'll go to wherever I go downtown, it's general.
Thursday, they're having a dedication to the county courthouse, and the chairman asked me to, he wants me to wear my uniform and come down.
Well, if I was participating in the program, I would.
We just, yeah.
And I feel like, when I put on the uniform, I... You should be a participant.
A participant, and I want to do it with dignity.
Yeah.
Because it's the rank.
You don't just stand around.
Oh, yeah.
It's the rank, you know.
I respect it.
Yeah.
I respect it, and I try to live up to the expectations of a general officer.
Well, let's talk about one of those, and that's back to the leadership.
And it seems you met Patton.

And at the same time you met Eisenhower, we talked about this a little bit, Patton is sort of a kick-him-in-the-pants type leader, and Eisenhower is much more of a low-key, Bradley much more of a low-key type person.
And I was wondering what type of leader were you?
I wasn't a Patton type in the sense that I talked like Patton.
You really... That is rough, Alan.
I mean, you set some examples there.
I was my own man.
I was my own self.
I mean, I don't know how I can relate to Eisenhower or Patton or Bradley or...
I was a, I wasn't a talkative gentleman.
I didn't talk, I didn't say much.
And I didn't cuss.
Oh, I got mad and raised hell, you know.
Cussed too, but I wasn't a foul mouth.
Oh no, in fact, I was, I guarded
And I didn't like my officers to be foul-mouthed either.
If I did, I'd put a stop to it.
I think some of my education, my schooling at A&M in the sciences kind of refined me a little bit.
And I had some of my basketball aggressiveness, too.
And where I get on the basketball court in Hill, I was tough.
Had to be.
And to try to say I was a Patton, or an Eisenhower, or Bradley, or Artie Murphy, or Hollinsworth.
You were just a coconuts.
I was just coconuts.
Okay, here's another question.
The nickname I did get was Iron Man.
You had a nickname?
Iron Man.
Iron Man.
I got that from basketball.
And it stayed with me.
It stayed with you throughout your entire life?
I don't know how the Army picked it up, but I was known as the Iron Man.
In fact, my... Yeah.
Let me show you.
Is it running?
I'll turn it on.
Iron Mike.
Why do you think you were called the Iron Man?
Well, at A&M they called me Iron Man because I played 40 minutes of basketball.
Well, why do you think they picked it up in the service?
Because I was the same way.
I guess I'd get up in the mornings and go, and in the evenings I was still going.
I was kind.
Well, iron usually sounds like somebody who's stern, inflexible, narrow-minded.
But it doesn't seem like that.
It doesn't seem like when you mention leadership, the type you were, you don't seem like you were tough or inflexible or narrow-minded or any of those.
You're cold.
Iron is cold.
Well, I think the Iron Man came in because of my durability.
Oh, durability.
Durability.
Because I'd stay in training, get up 4.30, 5 o'clock in the morning for Reveille and get going.
And then at night, at midnight, I'd be out in the bivouac areas, just visiting with the company commanders and see what they're doing, and go back to bed.
And I was up again next morning leading PT.
That's one reason why the second brigade
The staff officers liked me so well because the first time I went to summer camp, the first order of business was PT for the officers.
And the sergeant major was out there selling tickets to enlistment to see the officers doing PT because they'd never done it before.
PT, physical training.
Oh, okay.
You know, it was kind of a...
The sergeant major was kind of a sense of humor thing for me.
It was all right.
They loved it.
But, I don't know, leadership, that was myself, you know.
Okay, here's the assignment.
Let's say as a general, and maybe in the past or in the future you will be asked, but as a general you're asked to come back to A&M and give a talk, a short talk to the Corps on leadership.
What would you tell them?
If they want to know how to become leaders, what would you tell them?
you know out of 2000, maybe two will ever make it.
Not an easy question.
No, it's not.
It really isn't.
And you can't sum it up in just a few words either.
You really can't.
I mean, you can't come up with a cliche and say this is what leadership is.
Leadership is all the aspects that you have in you to do the best
job that you can with the best tools that you have inside.
I think the main thing is you've got to self-discipline yourself to just do.
I'll tell you.
You self-dip yourself, and you've got to obey the laws, written laws or unwritten laws, of good behavior and common sense.
You've got to know between right and wrong.
If you don't know what's right, then you'll never become a good leader.
So you've got to know what's right, and you've got to obey the law.
Whatever the law, you've got to be a law-abiding person.
You can't disregard the laws of the land and expect to be a leader.
It's not easy, you know.
You've got to be yourself.
If you try to imitate somebody else, you're going to just screw up right down the line.
You can't imitate.
You can emulate someone.
Take the good points of people and try to use it within you to lead your people.
Ask me some more questions.
OK, fine.

I want to turn to something now away from the military and away from leadership, and basically my final topic, and that is I want to discuss the major changes at A&M and your opinion of those changes over the last two decades.
In this place, it's been known as a conservative institution.
It's really changed radically.
from 6,000 students in 1960 to 34,000, admitting women and black.
And everything has grown in just phenomenal proportions.
And I'd like to have your opinions about that.
Let's start with women.
Do you think this is a positive change, or what do you think about women being allowed at A&M?
I think it's a positive change.
I think it's good for A&M.
I'm surprised it wasn't done sooner.
Because there's no reason to, even when the Corps, when it was all military, there's no reason to exclude women.
They could have fitted right in and getting their education right now.
As it turns out now, it's the best thing that happened to A&M.
They're the best Aggie supporters we got, the women.
My daughter, Elise, she's got more Aggie spirit than all of us put together.
So is Suzanne.
Suzanne Bruce.
And so I think it was a very positive step to find women to come down there.
OK, now let's shift from women at A&M to women in the reserves.
You must have seen increases of women in the reserves during your career.
What were your feelings on that?
It wasn't a strong feeling, but it was OK.
They wanted to play a part of it, and there's a place for them.
We had them in World War II.
Sure did.
Yeah, over in Europe.
So there's no reason not to have them, yeah.
And the Red Cross girls were up front, too.
Instead of servicing supplies, they were giving us donuts and coffee.
So what's the difference, you know?
They were up front.
So I think it was a good experience.
and let the women join the reserve.
Did you have any problems as a commanding officer in the reserves with the women?
Was there any changes or problems that came up?
No problems at camp.
We went to camp with them, and of course, the latrine situation, and it was only sleeping quarters, and they had their own sleeping quarters and their own facilities, so that was no problem.
They ate in the mess hall with us.
They trained with us,
When I was in the 75th Mac, we went to the field, they went right along with us.
Never complained.
Cold, a lot of times it was cold up in Twin Falls, Minnesota.
Really?
Yeah, we went to Fort Ripley, Camp Ripley.
It was cold.
And the women were just right there.
And it was part of it.
It was nice to have women there.
What did you think of the average quality of the woman reserve?
Well, it wasn't.
as high as I thought it ought to be.
I tell you, it was average.
OK, now we've already talked about blacks in the reserve.
What were your thoughts on blacks coming to A&M, being allowed in A&M?
I think it was fine that they'd be given the opportunity to come to A&M.
Without lowering our standards, the SAT score or academic requirements, I think it's fine.
And as it turned out, I don't think we have any problem with it.
Do you know of any problem?
No.
I don't know of any problem.
They're in the band.
Yeah.
And that's really a spree outfit.
And so I think it's good.
Yeah.
Okay, what do you think of the idea of the end of the mandatory corps?
General Rudder ended the mandatory corps.
What did you think about that at the time of your ideas change?
And I know what you're talking about, your ideas.
Yeah, well, I've been thinking about what I told you, too.
At that time, at the time it happened, I knew it was good for the school, but I had some regrets.
that there would not be compulsory military training anymore at Texas A&M.
I think there should be compulsory military training, period.
And so with A&M doing away with it, it kind of made me feel a little sad because it deprived our army of some good officers.
And of course, that leads to the defense of our country.
And it was sad for that.
But at the time, General Rutter made that decision.
And it was a momentous decision for the school.
It had to be done.
Because the attitude of the people was going to change.
And it wouldn't have helped the progress of our university if they hadn't made that change.
We actually declined from 1950 to 1960.
We sure did.
And I kept up with it.
I'm sure all of them and I are the same way.
But I was aware that A&M was losing strength in their enrollment.
And something had to be done.
And I think General Rutter made a bold decision.
What did you think of General Rutter?
Did you know him?
I knew General Rutter very well.
Could you describe him?
Very strong person.
Kind person.
He was warm.
He'd see you, and he just, just as nice and friendly as he could be, remembered your name.
He remembered my name.
He remembered who I was.
And, you know, I played basketball for A&M.
Very likable person.
And he's the type of person that wasn't flamboyant.
In fact, matter of fact, you know, General Rutter began to put on a lot of weight.
I don't know if you, you know, and he, it didn't bother him.
He still soldiered because he, but that didn't bother him.
He, I mean, he's...
But he would expect the most out of us.
We gave him the most.
Very fine person.
Outstanding person.
Anybody scale the cliffs of France like he did, what can you say?
What do you think about the growth of the institution from 6,000 to 34,000?
I think it's grown a little bigger than I would like for it to be.
I think 30,000 is just a pretty good size.
I'm afraid it may get unwieldy.
I hope it doesn't get any larger.
Looks like a mine.
Yeah, I'm afraid so, because everybody loves A&M.
Golly, I get calls at the office, help me get my daughter a dormitory room.
She wants to go to A&M, and if she doesn't get a dormitory room, I'm not going to let her go.
Oh, yeah.
Really?
Oh, yeah.
I get them all the time.
No kidding?
Sure.
Oh, yeah.
That sort of must have made you feel good, but at the same time kind of sad.
Can you help her in any way?
No, I can't help her.
I didn't think so.
No.
And parents who went to Rice University or SMU would come to me and say, Hey, Mike, talk to my son and see if you can talk him into A&M.
Their parents want their children to go to A&M.
which makes me feel great.
A&M, I describe it as a very healthy school.
It really is.
No permissiveness.
It's a friendly school.
And the academics, well, it's just like Rudder wanted it.
It's an excellency.
And he did it because he built the graduate school up.
You know that?
Oh, yeah.
That's what did it.
That brought in some fine professors.
And that started the school in its academic height that it's reaching now.
But it doesn't really bother me, Terry, that so many people want to go to A&M.
It has to get bigger.
You can't stand still.
But I think A&M has kept in stride with its growth.
Unfortunately, we had this board that fired Jarvis Miller.
Well, I was sad by that.
And they got rid of Jack Williams.
What's going on?
Great guy.
Oh, Jack Williams.
Historian, too.
Huh?
Historian.
Yeah, yeah, that's right.
Great guy.
I consider him a true friend, a real friend.
Matter of fact, my son, Paige, was selling Bibles in West Virginia four summers ago.
They weren't really Bibles.
They were dictionaries, religious dictionaries.
Mm-hmm.
And he knocked on the door, and he had his Texas Aggie t-shirt on, and the lady came to the door, and he says, I'm Paige Coconuts from Texas A&M, and I'm here selling dictionaries.
She says, Paige, you're welcome to come into my house.
And Paige was taken aback.
She says, I'm Ms. Williamson.
Jack is my son.
Really?
That's right.
And so Paige and Ms. Williamson, they came back.
Real good friends.
She got sick, and Paige was there to assist her and help her, you know, and do anything he could.
But he spent three months up there.
And Jack Williamson was so grateful to Paige.
He said Paige was good medicine for his mother.
That he took Paige into his home, visited her, you know.
And still today, Paige could walk into his office anywhere, and he'd stop what he was doing, come in here, Paige.
You know, he said that medical stuff.
Well, what about the board?
What do you think about that?
I thought it was terrible.
I really do.
I think the board was wrong in doing what they did.
I think it was a power play for the board to try to ruin Dr. Williamson and Dr. Miller.
I kind of hope Miller comes back.
Do you think he will?
I think he's under consideration.
Have you heard?
No.
I've heard.
I've heard.
He's one of the top three.
Really?
And so is this Lamar president out here, Bob Kimball.
Very fine person.
A great person.
Dr. Kimball.
He's a West Point graduate.
He's also a Brigadier General.
Yeah.
He's a historian.
Is he?
Taught it at West Point for three years.
Really?
Yeah.
And so he's one of the top three.
He and Mark Miller and I don't know who the other four.
This is the story I hear.
But I thought the board did an injustice to Texas A&M.
We should have a more consistent policy.
It's hacking away at people.
I don't think that's the way you should treat people.
Well, it's only two people or one or two people on the board that does that.
And unfortunately...
They're too powerful.
Yeah.
Well, the chairman became too powerful.
He's one of them.
Well, the board calls the fire the quitting of Ballard.
I was president of the Texas A&M Letterman Association at the time.
And when they did that?
Yeah, when they did that.
Not one time, Terry, did I hear any complaints about Ballard from the alumni, or from the lettermen.
And we met every game in the lounge, and we always had a program, and there was always three or four hundred
People in there.
You ought to go in there sometime.
I wish you'd go in there.
It's beautiful.
Got pictures all over the wall.
All Americans.
Oh, yeah.
Yeah, you'd like it.
But they were in charge of firing.
I heard about that.
Of course, that was before I got here, but they told me in the archives that story about Billard.
Billard?
Well, you see, the board members were passing rumors around about getting rid of Billard, getting rid of Billard.
And so Billard heard it from his own staff people.
And he went to see Miller, and Miller said, no, no, no, you're not going to, Miller fired you.
And the lawyer says, hell you're not, I quit.
Wow.
They went out to Mississippi or something.
Yeah, Mississippi State, doing great.
Okay, I was wondering about,
One last issue.
The draft and registration of the draft is a big issue today.
And I was wondering, you said you wanted everybody to have compulsory military.
How would you do it?
What do you mean by that?
I would have the draft.
I would have every young man go into service for at least six or eight months.
Maybe not a year, but at least eight months.
Sort of an extended boot camp?
That's right.
And then a couple, maybe a couple months of specialty training.
Specialty training, specializes if he's in communications or if he's an artilleryman or infantry or signal or ordnance.
And then come back and get in the reserve program for two years.
I believe every young man that graduates from high school ought to do it.
Right then and immediately.
Right there, before he gets his start in college or
start in work or whatever you want to do immediately after graduating.
Sort of like universal military training.
Military training.
I was a proponent of that.
Old Truman's policy.
I was a proponent and I got on and I had many a discussion with the ministries here in Beaumont about that.
